		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Coherence (physics)</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Physics" title="Physics">physics</a>, <b>coherence</b> is a property of waves, that enables stationary (i.e. temporally and spatially constant) <a href="/wiki/Interference" title="Interference">interference</a>. More generally, coherence describes all <a href="/wiki/Correlation" title="Correlation">correlation</a> properties between <a href="/wiki/Physical_quantities" title="Physical quantities" class="mw-redirect">physical quantities</a> of a wave.</p>
<p>When interfering, waves add together to one big wave or destruct each other to a lot of smaller waves, depending on their relative <a href="/wiki/Phase_(waves)" title="Phase (waves)">phase</a>. Two waves are said to be coherent if they have a constant relative phase, which also implies that they have the same frequency. The <a href="/wiki/Degree_of_coherence" title="Degree of coherence">degree of coherence</a> is measured by the <a href="/wiki/Interference_visibility" title="Interference visibility" class="mw-redirect">interference visibility</a>, a measure of how perfectly the waves can cancel due to destructive interference.</p>
